# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aws-organizations
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] In physical security and information security, **access control** (**AC**) is the action of deciding whether a subject should be granted or denied access to an object (for example, a place or a resource).
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] The act of *accessing* may mean consuming, entering, or using.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] It is often used interchangeably with authorization, although the authorization may be granted well in advance of the access control decision.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] Access control on digital platforms is also termed admission control.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] The protection of external databases is essential to preserve digital security.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] Access control is considered to be a significant aspect of privacy that should be further studied.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] **Access control policy** (also **access policy**) is part of an organization’s security policy.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] In order to verify the access control policy, organizations use an access control model.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] General security policies require designing or selecting appropriate security controls to satisfy an organization's risk appetite - access policies similarly require the organization to design or select access controls.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] Broken access control is often listed as the number one risk in web applications.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] On the basis of the "principle of least privilege", consumers should only be authorized to access whatever they need to do their jobs, and nothing more.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] Geographical access control may be enforced by personnel (e.g. border guard, bouncer, ticket checker), or with a device such as a turnstile.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] There may be fences to avoid circumventing this access control.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] An alternative of access control in the strict sense (physically controlling access itself) is a system of checking authorized presence, see e.g.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] A variant is exit control, e.g. of a shop (checkout) or a country.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] The term access control refers to the practice of restricting entrance to a property, a building, or a room to authorized persons.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] Physical access control can be achieved by a human (a guard, bouncer, or receptionist), through mechanical means such as locks and keys, or through technological means such as access control systems like the mantrap.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] Within these environments, physical key management may also be employed as a means of further managing and monitoring access to mechanically keyed areas or access to certain small assets.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] Physical access control is a matter of who, where, and when.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] An access control system determines who is allowed to enter or exit, where they are allowed to exit or enter, and when they are allowed to enter or exit.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] Historically, this was partially accomplished through keys and locks.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] When a door is locked, only someone with a key can enter through the door, depending on how the lock is configured.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] Mechanical locks and keys do not allow restriction of the key holder to specific times or dates.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] Mechanical locks and keys do not provide records of the key used on any specific door, and the keys can be easily copied or transferred to an unauthorized person.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] When a mechanical key is lost or the key holder is no longer authorized to use the protected area, the locks must be re-keyed.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] Electronic access control (EAC) uses computers to solve the limitations of mechanical locks and keys.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] It is particularly difficult to guarantee identification (a critical component of authentication) with mechanical locks and keys.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] A wide range of credentials can be used to replace mechanical keys, allowing for complete authentication, authorization, and accounting.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] The electronic access control system grants access based on the credential presented.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] When access is granted, the resource is unlocked for a predetermined time and the transaction is recorded.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] When access is refused, the resource remains locked and the attempted access is recorded.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] The system will also monitor the resource and alarm if the resource is forcefully unlocked or held open too long after being unlocked.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] When a credential is presented to a reader, the reader sends the credential's information, usually a number, to a control panel, a highly reliable processor.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] The control panel compares the credential's number to an access control list, grants or denies the presented request, and sends a transaction log to a database.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] When access is denied based on the access control list, the door remains locked.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] If there is a match between the credential and the access control list, the control panel operates a relay that in turn unlocks the resource.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] The control panel also ignores an opening signal to prevent an alarm.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] Often the reader provides feedback, such as a flashing red LED for an access denied and a flashing green LED for an access granted.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] The above description illustrates a single factor transaction.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] Credentials can be passed around, thus subverting the access control list.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] For example, Alice has access rights to the server room, but Bob does not.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] Alice either gives Bob her credential, or Bob takes it; he now has access to the server room.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] To prevent this, two-factor authentication can be used.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] In a two factor transaction, the presented credential and a second factor are needed for access to be granted; another factor can be a PIN code, a second credential, operator intervention, or a biometric input.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] Passwords are a common means of verifying a user's identity before access is given to information systems.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] In addition, a fourth factor of authentication is now recognized: someone you know, whereby another person who knows you can provide a human element of authentication in situations where systems have been set up to allow for such scenarios.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] For example, a user may have their password, but have forgotten their smart card.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] In such a scenario, if the user is known to designated cohorts, the cohorts may provide their smart card and password, in combination with the extant factor of the user in question, and thus provide two factors for the user with the missing credential, giving three factors overall to allow access.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] A credential is a physical/tangible object, a piece of knowledge, or a facet of a person's physical being that enables an individual access to a given physical facility or computer-based information system.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] Typically, credentials can be something a person knows (such as a number or PIN code), something they have (such as an access badge), something they are (such as a biometric feature), something they do (measurable behavioural patterns), or some combination of these items.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] This is known as multi-factor authentication.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] The typical credential is an access card or key-fob, and newer software can also turn users' smartphones into access devices.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] There are many card technologies including magnetic stripe, bar code, Wiegand, 125 kHz proximity, 26-bit card-swipe, contact smart cards, and contactless smart cards.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] Also available are key-fobs, which are more compact than ID cards, and attach to a key ring.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] Biometric technologies include fingerprint, facial recognition, iris recognition, retinal scan, voice, and hand geometry.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] The built-in biometric technologies found on newer smartphones can also be used as credentials in conjunction with access software running on mobile devices.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] In addition to older more traditional card access technologies, newer technologies such as near-field communication (NFC), Bluetooth low energy or Ultra-wideband (UWB) can also communicate user credentials to readers for system or building access.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] Access control decisions are made by comparing the credentials to an access control list.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] This look-up can be done by a host or server, by an access control panel, or by a reader.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] The development of access control systems has observed a steady push of the look-up out from a central host to the edge of the system, or the reader.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] The predominant topology circa 2009 is hub and spoke with a control panel as the hub, and the readers as the spokes.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] The look-up and control functions are by the control panel.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] The spokes communicate through a serial connection; usually RS-485.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] Some manufactures are pushing the decision making to the edge by placing a controller at the door.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] Some readers may have additional features such as a display and function buttons for data collection purposes (i.e. clock-in/clock-out events for attendance reports), camera/speaker/microphone for intercom, or smart card read/write support.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] All the RS-485-related advantages and disadvantages also apply.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] The advantages and disadvantages of IP controllers apply to the IP readers as well.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] The most common security risk of intrusion through an access control system is by simply following a legitimate user through a door, referred to as "tailgating".
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] Often, a legitimate user may hold the door for the intruder as an act of common courtesy.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] This risk can be minimized through security awareness training of the user population, or more active means such as turnstiles which admit only one person at a time.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] In very high-security applications, this risk is minimized by using a sally port (sometimes called a "security vestibule" or "mantrap"), where operator intervention is required, presumably after confirming valid identification.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] The second most common risk is from levering a door open by sheer brute force.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] This is relatively difficult on properly-secured doors with ruggedized strikes or high holding force magnetic locks.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] Fully-implemented access control systems include forced-door monitoring alarms.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] These vary in effectiveness, often failing from high false-positive alarms, poor database configuration, or lack of active intrusion monitoring.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] Most newer access control systems incorporate some type of "door prop" alarm to inform system administrators of a door left open longer than a specified length of time.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] The third most common security risk arises from natural disasters.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] In order to mitigate this risk, the structure of the building, down to the quality of the network and computer equipment is crucial.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] From an organizational perspective, the leadership will need to adopt and implement an All Hazards Plan, or Incident Response Plan.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] The highlights of any incident plan recommended by the National Incident Management System usually include pre-incident planning, during-incident actions, disaster recovery, and after-action review.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] An attack similar to levering is breaking through cheap partition walls, typically made of wallboard or cinder blocks.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] In shared tenant spaces, the divisional wall is a vulnerability.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] A vulnerability along the same lines is the breaking of sidelight windows located next to doors.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] Spoofing of locking hardware is fairly simple and more elegant than levering.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] A strong magnet can operate the solenoid controlling bolts in electric locking hardware.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] Motorized locks, more prevalent in Europe than in the US, are also susceptible to this attack using a doughnut-shaped magnet.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] It is also possible to manipulate the power to the lock either by removing or adding current, although most Access Control systems incorporate battery back-up systems, and the locks are almost always located on the secure side of the door.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] Access cards themselves have proven vulnerable to sophisticated attacks.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] Enterprising hackers have built portable readers that capture the card number from a user's proximity card.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] The hacker simply walks by the user, reads the card, and later presents the number to a reader securing the door.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] This is possible when card numbers are sent in the clear, no encryption being used.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] To counter this, dual authentication methods, such as a card plus a PIN should always be used.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] Many access control credentials use unique serial numbers which are programmed in sequential order during manufacturing.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] In a method known as a "sequential attack", if an intruder has a credential once used in the system, they can simply increment or decrement the serial number until they find a credential that is currently authorized in the system.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] Specifying credentials with random unique serial numbers is recommended to counter this threat.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] In addition, increasingly long lockout timeout intervals after a credential failure will make automated repeated attacks infeasible.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] Finally, most electric locking hardware still uses mechanical keys as a fail-over.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] Most conventional mechanical key locks are vulnerable to bumping.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] In computer security, general access control includes authentication, authorization, and audit.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] A more narrow definition of access control would cover only access approval, whereby the system makes a decision to grant or reject an access request from an already authenticated subject, based on what the subject is authorized to access.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] Authentication and access control are often combined into a single operation, so that access is approved based on successful authentication, or based on an anonymous access token.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] Authentication methods and tokens include passwords, biometric analysis, physical keys, electronic keys and devices, hidden paths, social barriers, and monitoring by humans and automated systems.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] In any access-control model, the entities that can perform actions on the system are called *subjects*, and the entities representing resources to which access may need to be controlled are called *objects* (see also Access Control Matrix).
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] Subjects and objects should both be considered as software entities, rather than as human users: any human users can only have an effect on the system via the software entities that they control.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] In some models, for example the object-capability model, any software entity can potentially act as both subject and object.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] As of 2014, access-control models tend to fall into one of two classes: those based on capabilities and those based on access control lists (ACLs).
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] Both capability-based and ACL-based models have mechanisms to allow access rights to be granted to all members of a *group* of subjects (often the group is itself modeled as a subject).
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] Access to accounts can be enforced through many types of controls.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] Discretionary Access Control (DAC) In DAC, the data owner determines who can access specific resources.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] For example, a system administrator may create a hierarchy of files to be accessed based on certain permissions.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] Graph-based Access Control (GBAC) Compared to other approaches like RBAC or ABAC, the main difference is that in GBAC access rights are defined using an organizational query language instead of total enumeration.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] History-Based Access Control (HBAC) Access is granted or declined based on the real-time evaluation of a history of activities of the inquiring party, e.g. behavior, time between requests, content of requests.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] For example, the access to a certain service or data source can be granted or declined on the personal behavior, e.g. the request interval exceeds one query per second.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] History-of-Presence Based Access Control (HPBAC) Access control to resources is defined in terms of presence policies that need to be satisfied by presence records stored by the requestor.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] Policies are usually written in terms of frequency, spread and regularity.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] Identity-Based Access Control (IBAC) Using this network administrators can more effectively manage activity and access based on individual needs.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] Lattice-Based Access Control (LBAC) A lattice is used to define the levels of security that an object may have and that a subject may have access to.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] The subject is only allowed to access an object if the security level of the subject is greater than or equal to that of the object.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] Mandatory Access Control (MAC) In MAC, users do not have much freedom to determine who has access to their files.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] For example, security clearance of users and classification of data (as confidential, secret or top secret) are used as security labels to define the level of trust.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] Organization-Based Access Control (OrBAC) OrBAC model allows the policy designer to define a security policy independently of the implementation.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] Relationship-Based Access Control (ReBAC) A subject's permission to access a resource is defined by the presence of relationships between those subjects and resources.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] Role-Based Access Control (RBAC) RBAC allows access based on the job title.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] RBAC largely eliminates discretion when providing access to objects.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] For example, a human resources specialist should not have permissions to create network accounts; this should be a role reserved for network administrators.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] Rule-Based Access Control (RAC) RAC method, also referred to as Rule-Based Role-Based Access Control (RB-RBAC), is largely context based.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] Example of this would be allowing students to use labs only during a certain time of day; it is the combination of students' RBAC-based information system access control with the time-based lab access rules.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] Responsibility Based Access Control Information is accessed based on the responsibilities assigned to an actor or a business role.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] Subscription-Based Access Control (SBAC) SBAC assigns permissions based on a user's subscription status, automating the process of granting, modifying, or revoking access as users subscribe, upgrade, downgrade, or cancel.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] SBAC is particularly relevant for SaaS business, where access to features, data, or services is tied to a user's active plan.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] Unlike RBAC or ABAC, which define permissions based on roles or attributes, SBAC dynamically distributes roles and policies based on billing status, ensuring real-time access alignment.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] Several regulatory frameworks impose specific access control requirements on organizations handling sensitive data.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] The HIPAA Security Rule requires covered entities and business associates to implement technical access controls for electronic protected health information (ePHI), including unique user identification, emergency access procedures, automatic logoff, and encryption and decryption mechanisms.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] The proposed HIPAA Security Rule update (NPRM, December 2024) would strengthen these requirements by mandating multi-factor authentication for all access to ePHI.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] The Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS) Requirement 7 mandates that access to cardholder data be restricted on a need-to-know basis, while Requirement 8 requires unique identification for each person with computer access.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] The National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) addresses access control extensively in Special Publication 800-53 through the AC (Access Control) control family, which includes policies for account management, separation of duties, least privilege, and session controls.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] A technique used to define or restrict the rights of individuals or application programs to obtain data from, or place data onto, a storage device.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] The definition or restriction of the rights of individuals or application programs to obtain data from, or place data into, a storage device.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] The process of limiting access to the resources of an AIS (Automated Information System) to authorized users, programs, processes, or other systems.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] That function performed by the resource controller that allocates system resources to satisfy user requests.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] This definition depends on several other technical terms from Federal Standard 1037C.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] Special public member methods – **accessors** (aka **getters**) and **mutator methods** (often called **setters**) are used to control changes to class variables in order to prevent unauthorized access and data corruption.
[src:aws-organizations/access-control] In public policy, access control to restrict access to systems ("authorization") or to track or monitor behavior within systems ("accountability") is an implementation feature of using trusted systems for security or social control.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] Clients often use this in combination with autoscaling (a process that allows a client to use more computing in times of high application usage, and then scale down to reduce costs when there is less traffic).
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] These cloud computing web services provide various services related to networking, compute, storage, middleware, IoT and other processing capacity, as well as software tools via AWS server farms.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] This frees clients from managing, scaling, and patching hardware and operating systems.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] One of the foundational services is Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2), which allows users to have at their disposal a virtual cluster of computers, with extremely high availability, which can be interacted with over the internet via REST APIs, a CLI or the AWS console.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] AWS services are delivered to customers via a network of AWS server farms located throughout the world.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] Fees are based on a combination of usage (known as a "Pay-as-you-go" model), hardware, operating system, software, and networking features chosen by the subscriber requiring various degrees of availability, redundancy, security, and service options.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] Subscribers can pay for a single virtual AWS computer, a dedicated physical computer, or clusters of either.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] Amazon provides select portions of security for subscribers (e.g. physical security of the data centers) while other aspects of security are the responsibility of the subscriber (e.g. account management, vulnerability scanning, patching).
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] AWS operates from many global geographical regions, including nine in North America.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] Amazon markets AWS to subscribers as a way of obtaining large-scale computing capacity more quickly and cheaply than building an actual physical server farm.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] All services are billed based on usage, but each service measures usage in varying ways.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] As of 2023 Q1, AWS has 31% market share for cloud infrastructure while the next two competitors Microsoft Azure and Google Cloud have 25%, and 11% respectively, according to Synergy Research Group.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] As of 2025 AWS comprises over 200 products and services including computing, storage, networking, database, analytics, application services, deployment, management, machine learning, mobile, developer tools, RobOps and tools for the Internet of Things.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] The most popular include Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2), Amazon Simple Storage Service (Amazon S3), Amazon Connect, and AWS Lambda (a serverless function that can perform arbitrary code written in any language that can be configured to be triggered by hundreds of events, including HTTP calls).
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] Services expose functionality through APIs for clients to use in their applications.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] These APIs are accessed over HTTP, using the REST architectural style and SOAP protocol for older APIs and exclusively JSON for newer ones.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] Clients can interact with these APIs in various ways, including from the AWS console (a website), by using SDKs written in various languages (such as Python, Java, and JavaScript), or by making direct REST calls.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] The genesis of AWS came in the early 2000s.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] After building *Merchant.com*, Amazon's e-commerce-as-a-service platform that offers third-party retailers a way to build their own web-stores, Amazon pursued service-oriented architecture as a means to scale its engineering operations, led by then CTO Allan Vermeulen.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] He also called for increasing the percentage of the time engineers spent building the software rather than doing other tasks.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] Amazon created "a shared IT platform" so its engineering organizations, which were spending 70% of their time on "undifferentiated heavy-lifting" such as IT and infrastructure problems, could focus on customer-facing innovation instead.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] In July 2002 Amazon.com Web Services, managed by Colin Bryar, launched its first web services, opening up the Amazon.com platform to all developers.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] Over one hundred applications were built on top of it by 2004.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] This unexpected developer interest took Amazon by surprise and convinced them that developers were "hungry for more".
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] By the summer of 2003, Andy Jassy had taken over Bryar's portfolio at Rick Dalzell's behest, after Vermeulen, who was Bezos' first pick, declined the offer.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] Jassy subsequently mapped out the vision for an "Internet OS" made up of foundational infrastructure primitives that alleviated key impediments to shipping software applications faster.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] By fall 2003, databases, storage, and compute were identified as the first set of infrastructure pieces that Amazon should launch.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] According to Brewster Kahle, co-founder of Alexa Internet, which was acquired by Amazon in 1999, his start-up's compute infrastructure helped Amazon solve its big data problems and later informed the innovations that underpinned AWS.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] Jassy assembled a founding team of 57 employees from a mix of engineering and business backgrounds to kick-start these initiatives, with a majority of the hires coming from outside the company.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] They included Jeff Lawson, the Twilio CEO; Adam Selipsky, the Tableau CEO; and Mikhail Seregine, a co-founder at Outschool.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] Near the end of their paper, they mentioned the possibility of selling access to virtual servers as a service, proposing the company could generate revenue from the new infrastructure investment.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] Thereafter Pinkham, Willem van Biljon, and lead developer Christopher Brown developed the Amazon EC2 service, with a team in Cape Town, South Africa.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] In October 2004, Amazon released Alexa Web Information Service (AWIS) as beta.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] In November 2004, AWS launched its first infrastructure service, as beta: Simple Queue Service (SQS)., and officially launched in July 2006.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] On March 14, 2006, AWS launched Amazon S3 cloud storage, and that was the first AWS' IaaS that was generally available, followed by EC2 in August 2006.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] Pi Corporation, a startup Paul Maritz co-founded, was the first beta-user of EC2 outside of Amazon, while Microsoft was among EC2's first enterprise customers.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] Later that year SmugMug, one of the early AWS adopters, attributed savings of around US$400,000 in storage costs to S3.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] According to Vogels, S3 was built with 8 microservices when it launched in 2006 and had over 300 microservices by 2022.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] In September 2007, AWS announced its annual *Start-up Challenge*, a contest with prizes worth $100,000 for entrepreneurs and software developers in the US using AWS services such as S3 and EC2 to build their businesses.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] The first edition saw participation from Justin.tv, which Amazon later acquired in 2014.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] Ooyala, an online media company, was the eventual winner.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] AWS offers, as of June 16, 2022, two block-storage options: the EC2 Instance Store and the Elastic Block Store (EBS).
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] Additional AWS services from this period include SimpleDB, Mechanical Turk, Elastic Beanstalk, Relational Database Service, DynamoDB, CloudWatch, Simple Workflow, CloudFront, and Availability Zones.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] In November 2010, it was reported that all of Amazon.com's retail sites had migrated to AWS.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] Prior to 2012, AWS was considered a part of Amazon.com and so its revenue was not delineated in Amazon financial statements.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] In that year industry watchers for the first time estimated AWS revenue to be over $1.5 billion.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] On November 27, 2012, AWS hosted its first major annual conference, *re:Invent* with a focus on AWS's partners and ecosystem, with over 150 sessions.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] The three-day event was held in Las Vegas because of its relatively cheaper connectivity with locations across the United States and the rest of the world.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] Andy Jassy and Werner Vogels presented keynotes, with Jeff Bezos joining Vogels for a fireside chat.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] AWS opened early registrations at US$1,099 per head for their customers from over 190 countries.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] On stage with Andy Jassy at the event which saw around 6000 attendees, Reed Hastings, CEO at Netflix, announced plans to migrate 100% of Netflix's infrastructure to AWS.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] To support industry-wide training and skills standardization, AWS began offering a certification program for computer engineers, on April 30, 2013, to highlight expertise in cloud computing.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] Later that year, in October, AWS launched *Activate*, a program for start-ups worldwide to leverage AWS credits, third-party integrations, and free access to AWS experts to help build their business.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] In 2014, AWS launched its partner network, AWS Partner Network (APN), which is focused on helping AWS-based companies grow and scale the success of their business with close collaboration and best practices.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] In October 2014, Amazon Aurora was launched.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] In January 2015, Amazon Web Services acquired Annapurna Labs, an Israel-based microelectronics company for a reported US$350–370M.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] In April 2015, Amazon.com reported AWS was profitable, with sales of $1.57 billion in the first quarter of the year and $265 million of operating income.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] Founder Jeff Bezos described it as a fast-growing $5 billion business; analysts described it as "surprisingly more profitable than forecast".
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] In October, Amazon.com said in its Q3 earnings report that AWS's operating income was $521 million, with operating margins at 25 percent.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] AWS's 2015 Q3 revenue was $2.1 billion, a 78% increase from 2014's Q3 revenue of $1.17 billion.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] 2015 Q4 revenue for the AWS segment increased 69.5% y/y to $2.4 billion with a 28.5% operating margin, giving AWS a $9.6 billion run rate.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] In 2015, Gartner estimated that AWS customers are deploying 10x more infrastructure on AWS than the combined adoption of the next 14 providers.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] In 2016 Q1, revenue was $2.57 billion with net income of $604 million, a 64% increase over 2015 Q1 that resulted in AWS being more profitable than Amazon's North American retail business for the first time.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] Jassy was thereafter promoted to CEO of the division.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] Around the same time, Amazon experienced a 42% rise in stock value as a result of increased earnings, of which AWS contributed 56% to corporate profits.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] AWS had $17.46 billion in annual revenue in 2017.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] By the end of 2020, the number had grown to $46 billion.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] Reflecting the success of AWS, Jassy's annual compensation in 2017 hit nearly $36 million.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] In January 2018, Amazon launched a unified autoscaling service on AWS.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] This new service unifies and builds on AWS existing, service-specific, scaling features like EC2 Auto Scaling groups, that was launched in August 2006.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] In November 2018, AWS announced customized ARM cores for use in its servers.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] Also in November 2018, AWS created ground stations to communicate with customers' satellites.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] In 2019, AWS reported 37% yearly growth and accounted for 12% of Amazon's revenue (up from 11% in 2018).
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] In April 2021, AWS reported 32% yearly growth and accounted for 32% of $41.8 billion cloud market in Q1 2021.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] In January 2022, AWS joined the MACH Alliance, a non-profit enterprise technology advocacy group.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] In June 2022, it was reported that in 2019 Capital One had not secured their AWS resources properly, and was subject to a data breach by a former AWS employee.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] The employee was convicted of hacking into the company's cloud servers to steal customer data and use computer power to mine cryptocurrency.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] The ex-employee was able to download the personal information of more than 100 million Capital One customers.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] In June 2022, AWS announced they had launched the AWS Snowcone, a small computing device, to the International Space Station on the Axiom Mission 1.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] In September 2023, AWS announced it would become AI startup Anthropic's primary cloud provider.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] Amazon has committed to investing up to $4 billion in Anthropic and will have a minority ownership position in the company.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] In April 2024, AWS announced a new service called Deadline Cloud, which lets customers set up, deploy and scale up graphics and visual effects rendering pipelines on AWS cloud infrastructure.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] In July 2024, AWS won a $1.3 billion (A$2 billion) contract with Australia's government to build a top-secret cloud service.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] The service included a partnership with the Australian Signals Directorate (ASD).
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] The ASD director general Rachel Noble said the service would "provide a state-of-the-art collaborative space for our intelligence and defense community to store and access top-secret data”.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] In December 2024, AWS announced Amazon Nova, its own family of foundation models.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] These models, offered through Amazon Bedrock, are designed for various tasks including content generation, video understanding, and building agentic applications.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] They are available in six different sizes.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] In March and April of 2026, during the 2026 Iran War, Iranian drone and missile strikes damaged AWS data centers in the United Arab Emirates (me-central-1) and Bahrain (me-south-1) regions, in the first deliberate military targeting of a commercial data center.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] Iran claimed the data centers hosted US military workloads.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] AWS advised customers to migrate to other regions.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] In October 2013, AWS was awarded a $600M contract with the CIA.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] By 2019, it was reported that more than 80% of Germany's listed DAX companies used AWS.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] Navy said it moved 72,000 users from six commands to an AWS cloud system as a first step toward pushing all of its data and analytics onto the cloud.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] In January 2021, Amazon announced that it would suspend Parler from Amazon Web Services, stating Parler hosted “violent content” that violates its terms of service.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] Later in 2021, DISH Network announced it would develop and launch its 5G network on AWS.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] It was also reported that spy agencies and government departments in the UK, such as GCHQ, MI5, MI6, and the Ministry of Defence, contracted AWS to host their classified materials.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] In 2022, Amazon shared a $9 billion contract from the United States Department of Defense for cloud computing with Google, Microsoft, and Oracle.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] AWS won a $581 million contract from the U.S.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] Air Force in January 2026 to provide cloud services and specific Amazon data centers as part of the Cloud One Program, the Air Force's enterprise cloud environment.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] Multiple financial services firms have shifted to AWS in some form.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] Notable customers include NASA and the Obama presidential campaign of 2012.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] As of October 2025, AWS has distinct operations in 38 geographical "regions": nine in North America, two in South America, nine in Europe, four in the Middle East, one in Africa, thirteen in the Asia–Pacific, and three in Australia and New Zealand.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] Most AWS regions are enabled by default for AWS accounts.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] Regions introduced after 20 March 2019 are considered to be *opt-in* regions, requiring a user to explicitly enable them in order for the region to be usable in the account.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] For opt-in regions, Identity and Access Management (IAM) resources such as users and roles are only propagated to the regions that are enabled.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] Each region is wholly contained within a single country and all of its data and services stay within the designated region.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] Each region has multiple "Availability Zones", which consist of one or more discrete data centers, each with redundant power, networking, and connectivity, housed in separate facilities.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] Availability Zones do not automatically provide additional scalability or redundancy within a region, since they are intentionally isolated from each other to prevent outages from spreading between zones.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] Several services can operate across Availability Zones (e.g., S3, DynamoDB) while others can be configured to replicate across zones to spread demand and avoid downtime from failures.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] As of December 2014, Amazon Web Services operated an estimated 1.4 million servers across 11 regions and 28 availability zones.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] As of March 2024, AWS had announced the planned launch of six additional regions in Malaysia, Mexico, New Zealand, Thailand, Saudi Arabia, and the European Union.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] In mid March 2023, Amazon Web Services signed a cooperation agreement with the New Zealand Government to build large data centers in New Zealand.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] AWS also has "pop-up lofts" in different locations around the world.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] These market AWS to entrepreneurs and startups in different tech industries in a physical location.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] Visitors can work or relax inside the loft, or learn more about what they can do with AWS.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] In June 2014, AWS opened their first temporary pop-up loft in San Francisco.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] In May 2015 they expanded to New York City, and in September 2015 expanded to Berlin.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] AWS opened its fourth location, in Tel Aviv from March 1, 2016, to March 22, 2016.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] A pop-up loft was open in London from September 10 to October 29, 2015.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] The pop-up lofts in New York and San Francisco are indefinitely closed due to the COVID-19 pandemic while Tokyo has remained open in a limited capacity.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] In 2017, AWS launched AWS re/Start in the United Kingdom to help young adults and military veterans retrain in technology-related skills.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] In partnership with the Prince's Trust and the Ministry of Defence (MoD), AWS will help to provide re-training opportunities for young people from disadvantaged backgrounds and former military personnel.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] AWS is working alongside a number of partner companies including Cloudreach, Sage Group, EDF Energy, and Tesco Bank.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] In April 2022, AWS announced that the organization had committed more than $30 million over three years to early-stage start-ups led by Black, Latino, LGBTQIA+, and women founders as part of its AWS impact Accelerator.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] The Initiative offers qualifying start-ups up to $225,000 in cash, credits, extensive training, mentoring, technical guidance and includes up to $100,000 in AWS service credits.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] In 2014, AWS claimed its aim was to achieve 100% renewable energy usage in the future.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] In 2016, Greenpeace assessed major tech companies—including cloud services providers like AWS, Microsoft, Oracle, Google, IBM, Salesforce and Rackspace—based on their level of "clean energy" usage.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] Greenpeace evaluated companies on their mix of renewable-energy sources; transparency; renewable-energy commitment and policies; energy efficiency and greenhouse-gas mitigation; renewable-energy procurement; and advocacy.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] The group gave AWS an overall "C" grade.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] Greenpeace credited AWS for its advances toward greener computing in recent years and its plans to launch multiple wind and solar farms across the United States.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] The organization stated that Amazon is opaque about its carbon footprint.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] In January 2021, AWS joined an industry pledge to achieve climate neutrality of data centers by 2030, the Climate Neutral Data Centre Pact.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] As of 2023, Amazon as a whole is the largest corporate purchaser of renewable energy in the world, a position it has held since 2020, and has a global portfolio of over 20 GW of renewable energy capacity.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] In 2022, 90% of all Amazon operations, including data centers, were powered by renewables.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] In 2024, AWS paid $650 million for a data center at the 2.5 GW Susquehanna nuclear power plant, connected at 300 MW.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] The power increase depends on Amazon's expansion of the data center.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] US Department of Homeland Security has employed the software ATLAS, which runs on Amazon Cloud.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] It scanned more than 16.5 million records of naturalized Americans and flagged approximately 124,000 of them for manual analysis and review by USCIS officers regarding denaturalization.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] Some of the scanned data came from the Terrorist Screening Database and the National Crime Information Center.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] The algorithm and the criteria for the algorithm were secret.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] Amazon faced protests from its own employees and activists for the anti-migrant collaboration with authorities.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] The contract for Project Nimbus drew rebuke and condemnation from the companies' shareholders as well as their employees, over concerns that the project would lead to abuses of Palestinians' human rights in the context of the ongoing occupation and the Israeli–Palestinian conflict.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] Specifically, they voice concern over how the technology will enable further surveillance of Palestinians and unlawful data collection on them as well as facilitate the expansion of Israel's illegal settlements on Palestinian land.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] A government procurement document featuring 'obligatory customers' of Nimbus, including "two of Israel’s leading state-owned weapons manufacturers" Israel Aerospace Industries and Rafael Advanced Defense Systems, was published in 2021 with periodic updates since (up to Oct 2023).
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] AWS has been noted to work with Chinese companies under varying degrees of U.S. government sanctions, such as Hikvision and Dahua Technology, which have been accused to enabling mass surveillance and human rights abuses in China and elsewhere.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] In July 2025, a security researcher disclosed a supply-chain vulnerability in the Amazon Q Developer Extension (version 1.84) for Visual Studio Code.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] The issue involved a malicious pull request to the project's GitHub repository, which introduced a prompt instructing the AI assistant to delete local files and AWS resources.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] AWS acknowledged the issue in Security Bulletin AWS‑2025‑015 and released version 1.85 to remove the injected prompt.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] The company stated that no customer systems or data were affected.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] However, critics including Corey Quinn, writing in Last Week in AWS, questioned the transparency of the response, noting the absence of a changelog entry, a CVE assignment, or a public statement beyond the bulletin.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] In response to the Log4Shell vulnerability, AWS released hot patch solutions to mitigate risks in Java applications across various environments, including standalone servers, Kubernetes clusters, and Elastic Container Service (ECS).
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] These patches were designed for both AWS and non-AWS environments.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] However, researchers from Unit 42 at Palo Alto Networks identified critical security flaws in these patches that could be exploited for container escape and privilege escalation, potentially granting attackers unauthorized root-level access to the host system.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] AWS addressed these vulnerabilities by releasing updated patches on April 19, 2022.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] Users who deployed the initial patches were advised to upgrade to the latest versions to mitigate security risks.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] In April 2024, security researchers from Miggo security identified a configuration vulnerability in AWS Application Load Balancer (ALB) that could allow attackers to bypass access controls and compromise web applications.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] The issue stemmed from how some users configured ALB's authentication handoff to third-party services, potentially enabling unauthorized access to application data.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] On July 11, 2024, AWS confirmed the issue affecting its customers, and on July 19, 2024, AWS updated its documentation accordingly to recommend more secure implementation practices.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] In 2026, Amazon Web Services (AWS) data center infrastructure in the United Arab Emirates and Bahrain experienced service disruptions following reported drone strikes in the region.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] AWS applies charges for data transferred both between Availability Zones within the same region (inter-AZ) and across different geographic regions (inter-region).
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] The pricing structure is influenced by several factors, including the source and destination of the data, the specific AWS services in use, and the underlying networking architecture.
[src:aws-organizations/amazon-web-services] Various services implement different data transfer models, and the choice of communication method—such as VPC Peering, Transit Gateway, or AWS PrivateLink—can also affect the overall cost.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] "Governance" can also pertain to a specific sector of activities such as land, environment, health, internet, security, etc.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] The degree of formality in governance depends on the internal rules of a given entity and its external interactions with similar entities.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] As such, governance may take many forms, driven by many different motivations and with many different results.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] The most formal type of a governing body is a government, which has the responsibility and authority to make binding decisions for a specific geopolitical system (like a country) through established rules and guidelines.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] A government may operate as a democracy where citizens vote on who should govern towards the goal of public good.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] Beyond governments, other entities can also have governing bodies.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] These can be legal entities or organizations, such as corporations, companies or non-profit organizations governed by small boards of directors pursuing more specific aims.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] They can also be socio-political groups including hierarchical political structures, tribes, religious subgroups, or even families.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] In the case of a state, governance expresses a growing awareness of the ways in which diffuse forms of power and authority can secure order even in the absence of state activity.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] A variety of external actors without decision-making power can influence this system of state governance.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] These include lobbies, think-tanks, political parties, non-government organizations, community and media.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] Governance is also shaped by external factors such as globalization, social movements or technological progress.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] From a normative perspective, good, effective and fair governance involves a well-organized system that fairly represents stakeholders' interests and needs.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] Such governance guides the formulation, implementation, and evaluation of the group's objectives, policies, and programs, ensuring smooth operation in various contexts.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] It fosters trust by promoting transparency, responsibility, and accountability, and employs mechanisms to resolve disputes and conflicts for greater harmony.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] It adapts to changing circumstances, keeping the group responsive and resilient.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] By delivering on its promises and creating positive outcomes, it fosters legitimacy and acceptance of the governing body, leading to rule-compliance, shared responsibility, active cooperation, and ultimately, greater stability and long-term sustainability.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] Many institutions of higher education - such as the Balsillie School of International Affairs, Munk School of Global Affairs, Sciences Po Paris, Graduate Institute Geneva, Hertie School, and the London School of Economics, among others - offer governance as an academic subjects.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] Many social scientists prefer to use the term "governance" when discussing the process of governing, because it covers the whole range of institutions and involved relationships.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] This considers the process by which governments are selected, monitored and replaced; the capacity of the government to effectively formulate and implement sound policies and the respect of citizens and the state of the institutions that govern economic and social interactions among them.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] Like *government*, the word *governance* derives, ultimately, from the Greek verb *kubernaein* [*kubernáo*] (meaning *to steer*, the metaphorical sense first being attested in Plato).
[src:aws-organizations/governance] Its occasional use in English to refer to the specific activity of ruling a country can be traced to early-modern England, when the phrase "governance of the realm" appears in works by William Tyndale and in royal correspondence from James V of Scotland to Henry VIII of England.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] This usage of "governance" to refer to the arrangements of governing became orthodox including in Sidney Low's seminal text of the same title in 1904 and among some later British constitutional historians.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] Since then, the term has gained increasing usage.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] Governance can also define normative or practical agendas.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] Normative concepts of fair governance or good governance are common among political, public sector, voluntary, and private sector organizations.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] In its most abstract sense, governance is a theoretical concept referring to the actions and processes by which stable practices and organizations arise and persist.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] These actions and processes may operate in formal and informal organizations of any size; and they may function for any purpose, good or evil, for profit or not.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] Most theories of governance as process arose out of neoclassical economics.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] These theories build deductive models, based on the assumptions of modern economics, to show how rational actors may come to establish and sustain formal organizations, including firms and states, and informal organizations, such as networks and practices for governing the commons.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] Many of these theories draw on transaction cost economics.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] When discussing governance in particular organizations, the quality of governance within the organization is often compared to a standard of good governance.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] In the case of a business or of a non-profit organization, for example, good governance relates to consistent management, cohesive policies, guidance, processes and decision-rights for a given area of responsibility, and proper oversight and accountability.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] "Good governance" implies that mechanisms function in a way that allows the executives (the "agents") to respect the rights and interests of the stakeholders (the "principals"), in a spirit of democracy.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] Good governance is an indeterminate term used in international development literature to describe various normative accounts of how public institutions ought to conduct public affairs and manage public resources.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] These normative accounts are often justified on the grounds that they are thought to be conducive to economic ends, such as the eradication of poverty and successful economic development.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] Different organisations have defined governance and good governance differently.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] The effectiveness of governments is not a straightforward and consentient type of governance.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] Measurement and conceptualization of effectiveness is controversial and often used interchangeably with good governance.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] However, during the period of 1996–2018, an effort was made by the World Bank to create a comparable measure of the performance of governments; the Worldwide Governance Indicators (WGI).
[src:aws-organizations/governance] The WGI is constituted by over 30 databases which are rescaled and categorized into six categories; among these is government effectiveness.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] In short, effective governance is about quality of service, the independence of government and the quality of policies and implementation.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] Adding to these components, one might argue that responsiveness to citizen's needs is high in an effective government.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] Acting according to these needs, effectiveness is achieved by transparent, decentralized and neutral structures, that are consistent and disciplined.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] Therefore, efficient financial management, high-quality and committed personnel and formalized and standardized ways of processes is needed.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] For the latter, governments became much more efficient with the arise of bureaucracies.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] Nevertheless, governments in a rapidly changing environment need to be able to adapt quickly, so being bounded by rigid structures of functioning could work as a detriment.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] The components of effective governance described above all have a domestic character, within the boundaries of the national territory, national policies and about the inhabitants of a country.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] This is the internal aspect of effective governance, which mainly focuses on national services and policies.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] The external aspect of effective governance on the other hand, exclusively focuses on the international domain of politics.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] It entails the state's capacity to exercise its rights and fulfil its duties in alignment with international law, the representation of its people in the international political landscape and its participation in international relations.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] The purpose of effective governance in the internal aspect is to be the sovereign within its national territory; in the external aspect to wield sovereignty over international relations.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] For this reason, it is a necessary characteristic of the state to have unrestricted capacity to act, without any form of dependence in both state and international law.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] This independency is the core of statehood.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] In an attempt to identify predictors of effective government, a study was conducted to investigate what characteristics of the state are more deeply established by effective governance.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] The most striking conclusion was that effective governance has a big share in the economic growth and developing, although on the long term.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] However, this is a bi-directional relationship: economic growth does lead to more effective governance as well.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] Moreover, effective governance does have a positive influence on reducing corruption, strengthening political stability, contribution to improved rule of law and improved government spending and accountability.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] As is the case with economic development, it is plausible the argue that effective governance and the named predictors are a positive feedback cycle: they reinforce each other, and so indirectly themselves.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] When a state fails to govern effectively, this does not simply imply the absence of the characteristics of effective governance.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] First of all, the absence of effective governance is lack of capacity of the state to supply its inhabitants with political goods, such as rights and freedoms.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] Zartman describes how absence of effective governance comes about: "as the disintegration ofstate structure, authority (legitimate power), law, and political order".
[src:aws-organizations/governance] Five main characteristics are to be differentiated in the absence of effective governance: disorganizing of the structure of the processes in the state, violent conflicts, violations of human rights and social fragmentation, all of which have an endogenous character.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] Since the early years of the 2000s (decade), efforts have been conducted in the research and international development community to assess and measure the quality of governance of countries all around the world.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] Measuring governance is inherently a controversial and somewhat political exercise.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] A distinction is therefore made between external assessments, peer assessments and self-assessments.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] Examples of external assessments are donor assessments or comparative indices produced by international non-governmental organizations.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] An example of a peer assessment is the African Peer Review Mechanism.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] Examples of self-assessments are country-led assessments that can be led by government, civil society, researchers and/or other stakeholders at the national level.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] One of these efforts to create an internationally comparable measure of governance and an example of an external assessment is the Worldwide Governance Indicators project, developed by members of the World Bank and the World Bank Institute.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] The project reports aggregate and individual indicators for more than 200 countries for six dimensions of governance: voice and accountability, political stability and lack of violence, government effectiveness, regulatory quality, rule of law, control of corruption.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] A Worldwide Governance Index (WGI) was developed in 2009 and is open for improvement through public participation.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] The following domains, in the form of indicators and composite indexes, were selected to achieve the development of the WGI: Peace and Security, Rule of Law, Human Rights and Participation, Sustainable Development, and Human Development.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] Additionally, in 2009 the Bertelsmann Foundation published the Sustainable Governance Indicators (SGI), which systematically measure the need for reform and the capacity for reform within the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) countries.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] The project examines to what extent governments can identify, formulate and implement effective reforms that render a society well-equipped to meet future challenges, and ensure their future viability.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] Section 10 of the Government Performance and Results Act (GPRA) Modernization Act requires U.S. federal agencies to publish their strategic and performance plans and reports in machine-readable format.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] The International Budget Partnership (IBP) launched the Open Budget Initiative in 2006 with the release of the first Open Budget Survey (OBS).
[src:aws-organizations/governance] The OBS is a comprehensive analysis and survey that evaluates whether central governments give the public access to budget documents and provide opportunities for public participation in the budget process.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] To measure the overall commitment to transparency, the IBP created Open Budget Index (OBI), which assigns a score to each country based on the results of the survey.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] While the OBS is released biannually, the IBP recently released a new OBS Tracker, which serves as an online tool for civil society, the media, and other actors to monitor in real time whether governments are releasing eight key budget documents.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] The Open Budget Index data are used by the Open Government Partnership, development aid agencies, and increasingly investors in the private sector as key indicators of governance, particularly fiscal transparency and management of public funds.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] Examples of country-led assessments include the Indonesian Democracy Index, monitoring of the Millennium Development Goal 9 on Human Rights and Democratic Governance in Mongolia and the Gross National Happiness Index in Bhutan.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] Publishing performance reports openly on the Web in a standard, machine-readable format is good practice for all organizations whose plans and reports should be matters of public record.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] A collaborative governance framework uses a relationship management structure, joint performance and transformation management processes and an exit management plan as controlling mechanisms to encourage the organizations to make ethical, proactive changes for the mutual benefit of all the parties.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] Environmental governance are the processes of decision-making involved in the control and management of the environment and natural resources.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] These processes includes government, business and civil society.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] Environmental governance may also refer to a concept in political ecology which promotes environmental policy that advocates for sustainable human activity (i.e. that governance should be based upon environmental principles).
[src:aws-organizations/governance] Global governance (or world governance) comprises institutions that coordinate the behavior of transnational actors, facilitate cooperation, resolve disputes, and alleviate collective-action problems.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] Global governance entails making, monitoring, and enforcing rules.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] Within global governance, a variety of types of actors – not just states – exercise power.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] In contrast to the traditional meaning of governance, the term *global governance* is used to denote the regulation of interdependent relations in the absence of an overarching political authority.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] An example of this is the international system, or relationships between independent states.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] The concept of global governance began in the mid-19th century.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] It became particularly prominent in the aftermath of World War I, and more so after the end of World War II.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] Since World War II, the number of international organizations has also increased significantly.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] The number of actors involved in governance relationships—such as states, non-governmental organizations, firms, and epistemic communities—has also increased significantly.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] Various terms have been used for the dynamics of global governance, such as complex interdependence, international regimes, multilevel governance, global constitutionalism, and ordered anarchy.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] Mainly it seeks to strengthen the health system, making sure that they are capable of meeting the health needs of targeted populations.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] More broadly, health governance requires a synergistic set of policies, many of which reside in sectors other than health as well as governors beyond the national governments, which must be supported by structures and mechanisms that enable collaboration.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] For instance, in the European context, a health policy framework called Health 2020 Archived 2020-04-27 at the Wayback Machine was developed as a result of the collaboration between State members in the region.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] It gives policy-makers a vision, a strategic path and a set of priorities to improve health, guaranteeing that it is more equitable and sustainable.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] In the 21st century, global trends (e.g., changing population demographics and epidemiology, widening social inequalities, and a context of financial uncertainty) have influenced health system priorities and subsequently the setting of the health governance function.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] These trends have resulted in the emergence of joint actions of all stakeholders to achieve seminal changes in 21st-century societies.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] It is also important to consider that people have witnessed a global shift from traditional and reactive healthcare to proactive care, mainly enabled by investment in advanced technologies.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] Recent artificial Intelligence (AI) and Machine learning have made possible the automation as well as the standardisation of many processes in healthcare, which have also brought to light challenges to the existing governance structures.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] One of these challenges concerns the ownership of health data.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] "Metagovernance" is the "governing of governing".
[src:aws-organizations/governance] It represents the established ethical principles, or 'norms', that shape and steer the entire governing process.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] There are no clearly defined settings within which metagoverning takes place, or particular persons who are responsible for it.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] While some believe metagovernance to be the role of the state which is assumed to want to steer actors in a particular direction, it can "potentially be exercised by any resourceful actor" who wishes to influence the governing process.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] Examples of this include the publishing of codes of conduct at the highest level of international government, and media focus on specific issues at the sociocultural level.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] Despite their different sources, both seek to establish values in such a way that they become accepted 'norms'.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] The fact that 'norms' can be established at any level and can then be used to shape the governance process as whole, means metagovernance is part of both the input and the output of the governing system.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] Multi-level governance is the concept and study of the fact that many intertangled authority structures are present in a global political economy.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] The theory of multi-level governance, developed mainly by Liesbet Hooghe and Gary Marks, arose from increasing European integration, particularly through the European Union.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] Participatory governance focuses on deepening democratic engagement through the participation of citizens in the processes of governance with the state.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] The theoretical framework of participatory governance as a variant of governing can be dated back to the early 1990s when academics began to stress the need for citizen participation in the government process.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] This decentralization of state power "strength[ens] vertical accountability" improving the relationship between citizens and municipal governments.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] The idea is that citizens should play a more direct roles in public decision-making or at least engage more deeply with political issues.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] Government officials should also be responsive to this kind of engagement.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] In practice, participatory governance can supplement the roles of citizens as voters or as watchdogs through more direct forms of involvement.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] The role of citizens in participatory governance is to be afforded a form of state power as an elected group of non-political citizens to contribute to the public policy process.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] Different manifestations of participatory governance include participatory budgeting, councils, and community organizations involved at the state level, taking on state studies or participating in social issues.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] Over the last two decades, the most rapidly growing form of participatory governance has been participatory budgeting.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] In 2004, the British Columbia Citizens Assembly was the first form of direct citizen engagement created to envision the provincial electoral system.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] Action through participatory governance impacts policy at the municipal level.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] An example is the use of municipal housing councils in Brazil to impact policy adoption, which finds that housing councils are associated with a greater likelihood of program adoption beneficial to the needs reflected by the citizens.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] The mechanism of participatory governance links the social sphere to the political to produce policies directly molded by or influenced by citizens.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] Therefore, participatory governance potentially improves public service delivery and the allocation of resources.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] There is a distinction between the concepts of governance and politics.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] Politics involves processes by which a group of people (perhaps with divergent opinions or interests) reach collective decisions generally regarded as binding on the group, and enforced as common policy.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] Governance, on the other hand, conveys the administrative and process-oriented elements of governing rather than its antagonistic ones.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] This distinction assumes the possibility of the traditional separation between "politics" and "administration".
[src:aws-organizations/governance] Contemporary governance practice and theory sometimes questions this distinction, premising that both "governance" and "politics" involve aspects of power and accountability.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] Regulatory governance reflects the emergence of decentered and mutually adaptive policy regimes which rests on regulation rather than service provision or taxing and spending.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] The term captures the tendency of policy regimes to deal with complexity with delegated system of rules.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] It is likely to appear in arenas and nations which are more complex, more global, more contested and more liberally democratic.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] The term builds upon and extends the terms of the regulatory state on the one hand and governance on the other.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] While the term regulatory state marginalize non-state actors (NGOs and Business) in the domestic and global level, the term governance marginalizes regulation as a constitutive instrument of governance.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] The term regulatory governance therefore allows us to understand governance beyond the state and governance via regulation.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] Security sector governance (SSG) is a subpart concept or framework of security governance that focuses specifically on decisions about security and their implementation within the security sector of a single state.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] SSG applies the principles of good governance to the security sector in question.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] Emerging thinking about contract governance is focusing on creating a governance structure in which the parties have a vested interest in managing what are often highly complex contractual arrangements in a more collaborative, aligned, flexible, and credible way.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] Corporate governance refers to the mechanisms, processes, practices, and relations by which corporations are controlled and operated by their boards of directors, managers, shareholders, and stakeholders.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] Corporate governance consists of the set of processes, customs, policies, laws and institutions affecting the way people direct, administer or control an organization.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] Corporate governance also includes the relationships between people within an organization, (the stakeholders) and the corporate goals.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] The principal players include the shareholders, management, and the board of directors.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] Other stakeholders include employees, suppliers, customers, banks and other lenders, regulators, the environment and the community at large.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] IT governance primarily deals with connections between business focus and IT management.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] The goal of clear governance is to assure that investment in IT generates business value and mitigates the risks that are associated with IT projects.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] Land governance is concerned with issues of land ownership and tenure.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] It consists of the policies, processes and institutions by which decisions about the access to, use of and control over land are made, implemented and enforced; it is also about managing and reconciling competing claims on land.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] In developing countries, it is relevant as a tool to contribute to equitable and sustainable development, addressing the phenomenon that is known as 'land grabbing'.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] The operational dimension of land governance is land administration.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] Security of land tenure is considered to contribute to poverty reduction and food security, since it can enable farmers to fully participate in the economy.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] Without recognized property rights, it is hard for small entrepreneurs, farmers included, to obtain credit or sell their business – hence the relevance of comprehensive land governance.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] There is constant feedback between land tenure problems and land governance.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] For instance, it has been argued that what is frequently called 'land grabbing', was partly made possible by the Washington Consensus-inspired liberalization of land markets in developing countries.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] Many land acquisition deals were perceived to have negative consequences, and this in turn led to initiatives to improve land governance in developing countries.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] The quality of land governance depends on its practical implementation, which is known as land administration: 'the way in which rules of land tenure are made operational'.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] And another factor is accountability: the degree to which citizens and stakeholder groups are consulted and can hold to account their authorities.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] The main international policy initiative to improve land governance is known as the Voluntary Guidelines on the Responsible Governance of Tenure of Land, Fisheries and Forests in the Context of National Food Security (VGGT), endorsed by the Committee on World Food Security (CFS).
[src:aws-organizations/governance] Landscape governance roughly refers to the rules, processes and institutions according to which decisions regarding the protection, management and planning of the landscape are made.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] Landscape governance differs from country to country according to the national context (e.g., political system, organization of public administration, economy, culture etc.).
[src:aws-organizations/governance] The introduction of holistic approaches to landscape governance is the focus of the evolving interdisciplinary landscape research.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] Such an approach is the conceptualization of landscape as a commons.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] For example, insurance companies exert a great societal impact, largely invisible and freely accepted, that is a private form of governance in society; in turn, reinsurers, as private companies, may exert similar private governance over their underlying carriers.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] The term "public policy" should not be exclusively associated with policy that is made by government.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] Public policy may be created by either the private sector or the public sector.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] If one wishes to refer only to public policy that is made by government, the best term to use is "governmental policy", which eliminates the ambiguity regarding the agent of the policy making.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] Project governance is the management framework within which project decisions are made and outcomes of a project are realized.
[src:aws-organizations/governance] Its role is to provide a repeatable and robust system through which an organization can manage its capital investments—project governance handles tasks such as outlining the relationships between all groups involved and describing the flow of information to all stakeholders.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] An **organizational structure** defines how activities such as task allocation, coordination, and supervision are directed toward the achievement of organizational aims.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Organizational structure affects organizational action and provides the foundation on which standard operating procedures and routines rest.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] It determines which individuals get to participate in which decision-making processes, and thus to what extent their views shape the organization's actions.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Organizational structure can also be considered as the viewing glass or perspective through which individuals see their organization and its environment.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Organizations are a variant of clustered entities.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] An organization can be structured in many different ways, depending on its objectives.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] The structure of an organization will determine the modes in which it operates and performs.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Organizational structure allows the expressed allocation of responsibilities for different functions and processes to different entities such as the branch, department, workgroup, and individual.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Organizations need to be efficient, flexible, innovative and caring in order to achieve a sustainable competitive advantage.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Pre-bureaucratic (entrepreneurial) structures lack standardization of tasks.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] This structure is most common in smaller organizations and is best used to solve simple tasks, such as sales.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] The strategic leader makes all key decisions and most communication is done by one on one conversations.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] It is particularly useful for new (entrepreneurial) business as it enables the founder to control growth and development.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] They are usually based on traditional domination or charismatic domination in the sense of Max Weber's tripartite classification of authority.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] 214) gives the analogy that "the fully developed bureaucratic mechanism compares with other organizations exactly as does the machine compare with the non-mechanical modes of production.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Precision, speed, unambiguity, … strict subordination, reduction of friction and of material and personal costs- these are raised to the optimum point in the strictly bureaucratic administration." Bureaucratic structures have a certain degree of standardization.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] They are better suited for more complex or larger scale organizations, usually adopting a tall structure.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] The tension between bureaucratic structures and non-bureaucratic is echoed in Burns and Stalker's distinction between mechanistic and organic structures.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Bureaucratic structures have many levels of management ranging from senior executives to regional managers, all the way to department store managers.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Since there are many levels, decision-making authority has to pass through more layers than flatter organizations.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] A bureaucratic organization has rigid and tight procedures, policies and constraints.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] This kind of structure is reluctant to adapt or change what they have been doing since the company started.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Organizational charts exist for every department, and everyone understands who is in charge and what their responsibilities are for every situation.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Decisions are made through an organized bureaucratic structures, the authority is at the top and information is then flowed from top to bottom.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] This causes for more rules and standards for the company which operational process is watched with close supervision.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Some advantages for bureaucratic structures for top-level managers are they have a tremendous control over organizational structure decisions.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] This works best for managers who have a command and control style of managing.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Strategic decision-making is also faster because there are fewer people it has to go through to approve.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] A disadvantage in bureaucratic structures is that it can discourage creativity and innovation in the organization.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] This can make it hard for a company to adapt to changing conditions in the marketplace.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] The term of post bureaucratic is used in two senses in the organizational literature: one generic and one much more specific.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] In the generic sense the term post bureaucratic is often used to describe a range of ideas developed since the 1980s that specifically contrast themselves with Weber's ideal type bureaucracy.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] This may include total quality management, culture management and matrix management, amongst others.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] None of these however has left behind the core tenets of Bureaucracy.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Hierarchies still exist, authority is still Weber's rational, legal type, and the organization is still rule bound.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Heckscher, arguing along these lines, describes them as cleaned up bureaucracies, rather than a fundamental shift away from bureaucracy.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Another smaller group of theorists have developed the theory of the Post-Bureaucratic Organization, which attempts to describe an organization that is fundamentally not bureaucratic.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] This sort of horizontal decision-making by consensus model is often used in housing cooperatives, other cooperatives and when running a non-profit or community organization.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] It is used in order to encourage participation and help to empower people who normally experience oppression in groups.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Still other theorists are developing a resurgence of interest in complexity theory and organizations, and have focused on how simple structures can be used to engender organizational adaptations.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] For instance, Miner *et al.* (2000) studied how simple structures could be used to generate improvisational outcomes in product development.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Their study makes links to simple structures and improviser learning.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Other scholars such as Jan Rivkin and Sigglekow, and Nelson Repenning revive an older interest in how structure and strategy relate in dynamic environments.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] A functional organizational structure is a structure that consists of activities such as coordination, supervision and task allocation.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] The organizational structure determines how the organization performs or operates.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] The term "organizational structure" refers to how the people in an organization are grouped and to whom they report.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] One traditional way of organizing people is by function.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Some common functions within an organization include production, marketing, human resources, and accounting.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] This organizing of specialization leads to operational efficiency, where employees become specialists within their own realm of expertise.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] On the other hand, the most typical problem with a functional organizational structure is that communication within the company can be rather rigid, making the organization slow and inflexible.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Therefore, lateral communication between functions becomes very important, so that information is disseminated not only vertically, but also horizontally within the organization.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Communication in organizations with functional organizational structures can be rigid because of the standardized ways of operation and the high degree of formalization.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] As a whole, a functional organization is best suited as a producer of standardized goods and services at large volume and low cost.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Coordination and specialization of tasks are centralized in a functional structure, which makes producing a limited number of products or services efficient and predictable.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Moreover, efficiency can further be realized as functional organizations integrate their activities vertically so that products are sold and distributed quickly and at low cost.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] For instance, a small business could make components used in production of its products instead of buying them.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Even though functional units often perform with a high level of efficiency, their level of cooperation with each other is sometimes compromised.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Such groups may have difficulty working well with each other as they may be territorial and unwilling to cooperate.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] The occurrence of infighting among units may cause delays, reduced commitment due to competing interests, and wasted time, making projects fall behind schedule.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] This ultimately can bring down production levels overall, and the company-wide employee commitment toward meeting organizational goals.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] The divisional structure or product structure consists of self-contained divisions.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] A division is a collection of functions which produce a product.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] It also utilizes a plan to compete and operate as a separate business or profit center.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] According to Zainbooks.com, divisional structure in the United States is seen as the second most common structure for organization today.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Employees who are responsible for certain market services or types of products are placed in divisional structure in order to increase their flexibility.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Examples of divisions include regional (a U.S.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Division and an EU division), consumer type (a division for companies and one for households), and product type (a division for trucks, another for SUVs, and another for cars).
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] The divisions may also have their own departments such as marketing, sales, and engineering.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] The advantage of divisional structure is that it uses delegated authority so the performance can be directly measured with each group.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] This results in managers performing better and high employee morale.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Another advantage of using divisional structure is that it is more efficient in coordinating work between different divisions, and there is more flexibility to respond when there is a change in the market.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Also, a company will have a simpler process if they need to change the size of the business by either adding or removing divisions.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] When divisional structure is utilized more specialization can occur within the groups.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] When divisional structure is organized by product, the customer has their own advantages especially when only a few services or products are offered which differ greatly.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] When using divisional structures that are organized by either markets or geographic areas they generally have similar functions and are located in different regions or markets.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] This allows business decisions and activities coordinated locally.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] The disadvantages of the divisional structure is that it can support unhealthy rivalries among divisions.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] This type of structure may increase costs by requiring more qualified managers for each division.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Also, there is usually an over-emphasis on divisional more than organizational goals which results in duplication of resources and efforts like staff services, facilities, and personnel.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] The matrix structure groups employees by both function and product simultaneously.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] A matrix organization frequently uses teams of employees to accomplish work, in order to take advantage of the strengths, as well as make up for the weaknesses, of functional and decentralized forms.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] An example would be a company that produces two products, "product A" and "product B".
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Using the matrix structure, this company would organize functions within the company as follows: "product A" sales department, "product A" customer service department, "product A" accounting, "product B" sales department, "product B" customer service department, "product B" accounting department.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] There are advantages and disadvantages of the matrix structure.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Some of the disadvantages include tendencies towards anarchy, power struggles and 'sinking' to group and division levels.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Matrices increase the complexity of the chain of command, which can present problems because of the differentiation between functional managers and project managers.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] This, in turn, can be confusing for employees to understand who is next in the chain of command.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] An additional disadvantage of the matrix structure is higher manager to worker ratio that results in conflicting loyalties of employees.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] However, the matrix structure also has significant advantages that make it valuable for companies to use.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] The matrix structure may improve upon the "silo" critique of functional management in that it aims to diminish the vertical structure of functional and create a more horizontal structure which allows the spread of information across task boundaries to happen much quicker.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] It aims to allow specialization to increase depth of knowledge and allows individuals to be chosen according to project needs.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Starbucks is one of the numerous large organizations that successfully developed the matrix structure supporting their focused strategy.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Its design combines functional and product based divisions, with employees reporting to two heads.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Some experts also mention the multinational design, common in global companies, such as Procter & Gamble, Toyota and Unilever.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] This structure can be seen as a complex form of the matrix, as it maintains coordination among products, functions and geographic areas.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] In general, over the last decade, it has become increasingly clear that through the forces of globalization, competition and more demanding customers, the structure of many companies has become flatter, less hierarchical, more fluid and even virtual.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] The Flat organization is common in small companies (entrepreneurial start-ups, university spin offs).
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] As companies grow they tend to become more complex and hierarchical, which lead to an expanded structure, with more levels and departments.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] However, in rare cases, such as the examples of Valve, GitHub, Inc. and 37signals, the organization remains very flat as it grows, eschewing middle managers.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] (However, GitHub subsequently introduced middle managers).
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] All of the aforementioned organizations operate in the field of technology, which may be significant, as software developers are highly skilled professionals, much like lawyers.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Senior lawyers also enjoy a relatively high degree of autonomy within a typical law firm, which is typically structured as a partnership rather than a hierarchical bureaucracy.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Some other types of professional organizations are also commonly structured as partnerships, such as accountancy companies and GP surgeries.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Often, growth would result in bureaucracy, the most prevalent structure in the past.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] It is still, however, relevant in former Soviet Republics, China, and most governmental organizations all over the world.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Shell used to represent the typical bureaucracy: top-heavy and hierarchical.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] It featured multiple levels of command and duplicate service companies existing in different regions.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] All this made Shell apprehensive to market changes, leading to its incapacity to grow and develop further.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] The failure of this structure became the main reason for the company restructuring into a matrix.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] One of the newest organizational structures developed in the 20th century is *team* and the related concept of team development or team building.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] In small businesses, the team structure can define the entire organization.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Teams can be both horizontal and vertical.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] While an organization is constituted as a set of people who synergize individual competencies to achieve newer dimensions, the quality of organizational structure revolves around the competencies of teams in totality.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] The team could classified into functional team structure, lightweight team structure, heavyweight team structure and autonomous team structure.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] For example, every one of the Whole Foods Market stores, the largest natural-foods grocer in the US developing a focused strategy, is an autonomous profit centre composed of an average of 10 self-managed teams, while team leaders in each store and each region are also a team.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Larger bureaucratic organizations can benefit from the flexibility of teams as well.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Xerox, Motorola, and DaimlerChrysler are all among the companies that actively use teams to perform tasks.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] However, studies shows that this structure may have challenges for an organization.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] The scattered nature of team-based organizations makes it difficult for them to communicate and share information across borders, where knowledge exchange between and among teams and stakeholders becomes crucial as team-based organizing becomes the norm.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] However, this can be tackled by concentrate on their internal tasks as well as their relationships and connections with their multiple stakeholders, both inside and external to the firm.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Network organizations lack the hierarchical aspects of other structures and are characterized by clusters of interconnected teams and individuals that come together to form unique teams and complete certain projects or achieve common goals.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Participating agents are constrained by their specialization and role within the organization, but their influence varies with the development and dissolution of the projects and teams.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] For example, although an organization may have separate sales and marketing teams which each operate independently, certain projects will require individuals from those teams to work together and form partnerships for the length of their duration.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] This extends out to businesses on a larger scale, where instead of teams within an organization, the network consists of organizations within a market.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] While business giants risk becoming *too clumsy to proact (such as), act and react efficiently*, a network organization can contract out any business function that can be done better or more cheaply.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] In essence, these types of network structures' managers spend most of their time coordinating and controlling external relations, usually by electronic means.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] H&M is outsourcing its clothing to a network of 700 suppliers, more than two-thirds of which are based in low-cost Asian countries.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Not owning any factories, H&M can be more flexible than many other retailers in lowering its costs, which aligns with its low-cost strategy.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] The potential management opportunities offered by recent advances in complex networks theory have been demonstrated including applications to product design and development, and innovation problem in markets and industries.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] For these benefits to be realised, the network structure relies on trust through shared values and norms, actively avoiding hold-up problems and opportunism risks.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] By eliminating the uncertainty that one agent will use any potential gain in bargaining power for their singular gain, a network structure can avoid the associated inefficiencies that would arise.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] However, the potential disadvantages for enterprises adopting the networked organizational structure include unreasonable design, insufficient supervision and poor linkage ability.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] If the different relations required for the network structure contrast too greatly it may lead to confusion, delays, and unnecessary increases in complexity.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Due to the network structure relying on many different individuals or teams working together independently, effective supervision is needed to avoid shirking or free riding.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Similarly, some individuals and teams coordinate poorly, resulting in communication breakdowns and misunderstanding, which only hinders the progression of tasks.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Virtual organization is defined as being closely coupled upstream with its suppliers and downstream with its customers such that where one begins and the other ends means little to those who manage the business processes within the entire organization.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] A special form of boundaryless organization is *virtual*.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Hedberg, Dahlgren, Hansson, and Olve (1999) consider the virtual organization as not physically existing as such, but enabled by software to exist.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] The virtual organization exists within a network of alliances, using the Internet.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] This means while the core of the organization can be small but still the company can operate globally be a market leader in its niche.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] According to Anderson, because of the unlimited shelf space of the Web, the cost of reaching niche goods is falling dramatically.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Although none sell in huge numbers, there are so many niche products that collectively they make a significant profit, and that is what made highly innovative Amazon.com so successful.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] In the 21st century, even though most, if not all, organizations are not of a pure hierarchical structure, many managers are still blind to the existence of the flat community structure within their organizations.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] The business is no longer just a place where people come to work.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] For most of the employees, the firm confers on them that sense of belonging and identity –– the firm has become their "village", their community.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] The firm of the 21st century is not just a hierarchy which ensures maximum efficiency and profit; it is also the community where people belong to and grow together, where their affective and innovative needs are met.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Lim, Griffiths, and Sambrook (2010) developed the Hierarchy-Community Phenotype Model of Organizational Structure borrowing from the concept of Phenotype from genetics.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] "A phenotype refers to the observable characteristics of an organism.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] It results from the expression of an organism's genes and the influence of the environment.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] The expression of an organism's genes is usually determined by pairs of alleles.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] In our model, each employee's formal, hierarchical participation and informal, community participation within the organization, as influenced by his or her environment, contributes to the overall observable characteristics (phenotype) of the organization.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] "The Hierarchy-Community Phenotype Model of Organisational Structure views an organisation as having both a hierarchy and a community structure, both equally well established and occurring extensively throughout the organisation.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Organizational structures developed from the ancient times of hunters and collectors in tribal organizations through highly royal and clerical power structures to industrial structures and today's post-industrial structures.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Mohr, the early theorists of organizational structure, Taylor, Fayol, and Weber "saw the importance of structure for effectiveness and efficiency and assumed without the slightest question that whatever structure was needed, people could fashion accordingly.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Organizational structure was considered a matter of choice...
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] There are correspondences between Mintzberg's organizational archetypes and various approaches to military Command and Control (C2).
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Mintzberg's Machine Bureaucracy represents a highly centralized approach to C2, with a narrow allocation of decision rights, restricted patterns of interaction among organization members, and a restricted flow of information.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Mintzberg's Adhocracy, on the other hand, represents a more networked and less centralized approach to C2, with more individual initiative and self-synchronization.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] It involves a broader allocation of decision rights, broader interaction patterns, and broader information distribution.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Mintzberg's other organization types (for example, the Professional Bureaucracy and the Simple Structure) fall in between these two.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Moreover, Walker et. al states the event analysis for systematic teamwork (EAST) method as one of the military command and control approach provides a means of describing emergent system-level features that result from the intricate interactions of system constituents (human and technical).
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] They are modelled using task, social, and propositional networks and presented using an integrated methodologies approach.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] The social and technical principle of function and approximation, which states that similar individuals and the same technology may achieve the same objective via entirely distinct paths and entirely different starting points, is one important aspect of EAST.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] In addition, desirable emergent features, such as systems level "shared awareness", pace, agility, and self-synchronization might appear due to the indisputable reality that humans may adjust to the techno-organisational aspects of a particular system.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] The set organizational structure may not coincide with facts, evolving in operational action.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Such divergence decreases performance, when growing as a wrong organizational structure may hamper cooperation and thus hinder the completion of orders in due time and within limits of resources and budgets.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Organizational structures should be adaptive to process requirements, aiming to optimize the ratio of effort and input to output.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] An additional element is organisational ideology.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Entrepreneurial organisation or Simple structure has simple, informal structure.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Its leader coordinates the work using direct supervision.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] There is no technostructure, little support staff.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Such structure is usually found in organizations with environment that is simple (so that one man could have significant influence), but changing (so that flexibility of one man would give a significant advantage over the bureaucratic structures).
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Machine organisation or Machine bureaucracy has formal rules regulating the work, developed technostructure and middle line, is centralised, hierarchical.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Such structure is common when the work is simple and repetitive.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Organizations also tend to achieve such structure when they are strongly controlled from outside.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Also, such structure is common for organizations that perform work that is related to some sort of control (for example, prisons, police), or organizations with special safety requirements (for example, fire departments, airlines).
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Professional configuration or Professional bureaucracy mostly coordinates the work of members of operating core, professionals, through their training (for example, in university).
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Operating core in such organisation is large, middle line insignificant, as the professionals perform complex work and have significant autonomy.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Support staff, helping the professionals to do their job, is numerous.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Professionals participate in administrative work, thus there are many committees.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Such structure is common for universities, hospitals, law firms.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Diversified Configuration or Divisionalized form consists of several parts having high autonomy.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Such structure is common for old, large organizations.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Innovative Configuration or Adhocracy gathers the specialists of different fields into teams for specific tasks.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Such organizations are common when environment is complex and dynamic.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Mintzberg considers two types of such organization: operating adhocracy and administrative adhocracy.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Operating adhocracy solves innovative problems for its clients.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Examples of such organisation can be advertising agency or firm that develops the prototypes of products.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Administrative adhocracy has teams solving problems for the organization itself.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] As an example of such organization Mintzberg gives NASA when it worked on Apollo program.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Missionary organisation coordinates the work through organisational ideology.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Formal rules in such organization are not numerous.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Such organizations are decentralized, the differences between levels are not significant.
[src:aws-organizations/organizational-structure] Political configuration happens when the power is mostly used through workplace politics.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] In general, **compliance** means conforming to a rule, such as a specification, policy, standard or law.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] Compliance has traditionally been explained by reference to deterrence theory, according to which punishing a behavior will decrease the violations both by the wrongdoer (specific deterrence) and by others (general deterrence).
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] This view has been supported by economic theory, which has framed punishment in terms of costs and has explained compliance in terms of a cost-benefit equilibrium (Becker 1968).
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] However, psychological research on motivation provides an alternative view: granting rewards (Deci, Koestner and Ryan, 1999) or imposing fines (Gneezy Rustichini 2000) for a certain behavior is a form of extrinsic motivation that weakens intrinsic motivation and ultimately undermines compliance.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] Regulations and accrediting organizations vary among fields, with examples such as PCI-DSS and GLBA in the financial industry, FISMA for U.S. federal agencies, HACCP for the food and beverage industry, and the Joint Commission and HIPAA in healthcare.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] In some cases other compliance frameworks (such as COBIT) or even standards (NIST) inform on how to comply with regulations.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] Some organizations keep compliance data—all data belonging or pertaining to the enterprise or included in the law, which can be used for the purpose of implementing or validating compliance—in a separate store for meeting reporting requirements.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] Compliance software is increasingly being implemented to help companies manage their compliance data more efficiently.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] This store may include calculations, data transfers, and audit trails.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] The ISO also produces international standards such as ISO/IEC 27002 to help organizations meet regulatory compliance with their security management and assurance best practices.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] Some local or international specialized organizations such as the American Society of Mechanical Engineers (ASME) also develop standards and regulation codes.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] They thereby provide a wide range of rules and directives to ensure compliance of the products to safety, security or design standards.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] Regulatory compliance varies not only by industry but often by location.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] The financial, research, and pharmaceutical regulatory structures in one country, for example, may be similar but with particularly different nuances in another country.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] These similarities and differences are often a product "of reactions to the changing objectives and requirements in different countries, industries, and policy contexts".
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] These regulators help to ensure financial institutes meet their promises, that transactional information is well documented, and that competition is fair while protecting consumers.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] Australian organisations seeking to remain compliant with various regulations may turn to AS ISO 19600:2015 (which supersedes AS 3806-2006).
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] This standard helps organisations with compliance management, placing "emphasis on the organisational elements that are required to support compliance" while also recognizing the need for continual improvement.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] In Canada, federal regulation of deposits, insurance, and superannuation is governed by two independent bodies: the OSFI through the Bank Act, and FINTRAC, mandated by the Proceeds of Crime (Money Laundering) and Terrorist Financing Act, 2001 (PCMLTFA).
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] These groups protect consumers, regulate how risk is controlled and managed, and investigate illegal action such as money laundering and terrorist financing.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] On a provincial level, each province maintain individuals laws and agencies.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] Unlike any other major federation, Canada does not have a securities regulatory authority at the federal government level.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] The provincial and territorial regulators work together to coordinate and harmonize regulation of the Canadian capital markets through the Canadian Securities Administrators (CSA).
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] Other key regulators in Canada include the Canadian Food Inspection Agency (CFIA) for food safety, animal health, and plant health; Health Canada for public health; and Environment and Climate Change Canada for environment and sustainable energy.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] For more industry specific guidance, e.g., financial institutions, Canada's E-13 Regulatory Compliance Management provides specific compliance risk management tactics.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] Regulatory compliance in the European Union (EU) is governed by a harmonized legal framework designed to ensure consistency across member states while allowing for national implementation.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] EU compliance regulations cover various industries, including consumer product safety, financial services, environmental protection, and data privacy.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] The General Product Safety Regulation (GPSR) establishes a unified safety framework for consumer products across the EU, requiring manufacturers to conduct risk assessments, maintain traceability documentation, and meet safety compliance standards before placing products on the market.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] The GPSR applies to all consumer products made available in the EU unless covered by sector-specific regulations, such as medical devices or food products.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] The regulation extends to products sold through e-commerce platforms, requiring online marketplaces to ensure that only compliant products are listed.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] Fulfillment service providers are also included as economic operators, making them responsible for product safety compliance in certain cases.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] For business compliance, the EU’s regulatory approach is guided by the New Legislative Framework (NLF) and various sector-specific directives and regulations.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] Businesses must comply with EU product conformity assessments and affix the CE marking to indicate compliance with essential safety and performance standards.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] Financial compliance is enforced through regulations such as the Markets in Financial Instruments Directive (MiFID II) and the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), which set strict requirements for financial transparency, consumer protection, and data security.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] The EU Legislation Compliance framework ensures that organizations operate within the legal boundaries of EU directives, helping public and private entities manage regulatory risks efficiently.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] Companies operating in the EU must stay updated on evolving compliance requirements, as non-compliance can lead to fines, product recalls, or restrictions on market access.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] The financial sector in the Netherlands is heavily regulated.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] The Dutch Central Bank (De Nederlandsche Bank N.V.) is the prudential regulator while the Netherlands Authority for Financial Markets (AFM) is the regulator for behavioral supervision of financial institutions and markets.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] In India, compliance regulation takes place across three strata: Central, State, and Local regulation.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] India veers towards central regulation, especially of financial organizations and foreign funds.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] Compliance regulations vary based on the industry segment in addition to the geographical mix.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] Most regulation comes in the following broad categories: economic regulation, regulation in the public interest, and environmental regulation.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] India has also been characterized by poor compliance - reports suggest that only around 65% of companies are fully compliant to norms.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] The Monetary Authority of Singapore is Singapore's central bank and financial regulatory authority.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] It administers the various statutes pertaining to money, banking, insurance, securities and the financial sector in general, as well as currency issuance.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] There is considerable regulation in the United Kingdom, some of which is derived from European Union legislation.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] Various areas are policed by different bodies, such as the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA), Environment Agency, Scottish Environment Protection Agency, Information Commissioner's Office, Care Quality Commission, and others: see List of regulators in the United Kingdom.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] Important compliance issues for all organizations large and small include the Data Protection Act 2018 and, for the public sector, Freedom of Information Act 2000.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] Corporate scandals and breakdowns such as the Enron case of reputational risk in 2001 have increased calls for stronger compliance and regulations, particularly for publicly listed companies.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] The Office of Foreign Assets Control (OFAC) is an agency of the United States Department of the Treasury under the auspices of the Under Secretary of the Treasury for Terrorism and Financial Intelligence.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] OFAC administers and enforces economic and trade sanctions based on U.S. foreign policy and national security goals against targeted foreign states, organizations, and individuals.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] Compliance in the U.S. generally means compliance with laws and regulations.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] These laws and regulations can have criminal or civil penalties.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] The definition of what constitutes an effective compliance plan has been elusive.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] Most authors, however, continue to cite the guidance provided by the United States Sentencing Commission in Chapter 8 of the Federal Sentencing Guidelines.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] Small Business Administration re-launched Business.gov (later Business.USA.gov and finally SBA.Gov) which provides a single point of access to government services and information that help businesses comply with government regulations.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] Department of Labor, Occupational Health and Safety Administration (OSHA) was created by Congress to assure safe and healthful working conditions for working men and women by setting and enforcing standards and by providing training, outreach, education, and assistance.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] OSHA implements laws and regulations regularly in the following areas, construction, maritime, agriculture, and recordkeeping.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] The United States Department of Transportation also has various laws and regulations requiring that prime contractors when bidding on federally funded projects engage in good faith effort compliance, meaning they must document their outreach to certified disadvantaged business enterprises.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] Data retention is a part of regulatory compliance that is proving to be a challenge in many instances.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] The security that comes from compliance with industry regulations can seem contrary to maintaining user privacy.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] Data retention laws and regulations ask data owners and other service providers to retain extensive records of user activity beyond the time necessary for normal business operations.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] These requirements have been called into question by privacy rights advocates.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] Compliance in this area is becoming very difficult.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] Laws like the CAN-SPAM Act and Fair Credit Reporting Act in the U.S. require that businesses give people the right to be forgotten.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] In other words, they must remove individuals from marketing lists if it is requested, tell them when and why they might share personal information with a third party, or at least ask permission before sharing that data.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] Now, with new laws coming out that demand longer data retention despite the individual’s desires, it can create some real difficulties.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] Money laundering and terrorist financing pose significant threats to the integrity of the financial system and national security.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] To combat these threats, the EU has adopted a risk-based approach to Anti-Money Laundering and Combating the Financing of Terrorism (AML/CFT) that relies on cooperation and coordination between EU and national authorities.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] In this context, risk-based regulation refers to the approach of identifying and assessing potential risks of money laundering and terrorist financing and implementing regulatory measures proportional to those risks.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] However, the shared enforcement powers between EU and national authorities in the implementation and enforcement of AML/CFT regulations can create legal implications and challenges.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] The potential for inconsistent application of AML regulations across different jurisdictions can create regulatory arbitrage and undermine the effectiveness of AML efforts.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] Additionally, a lack of clear and consistent legal frameworks defining the roles and responsibilities of EU and national authorities in AML enforcement can lead to situations where accountability is difficult to establish.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] Corporate Governance Code (formerly the Combined Code) is issued by the Financial Reporting Council (FRC) and "sets standards of good practice in relation to board leadership and effectiveness, remuneration, accountability, and relations with shareholders".
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] All companies with a Premium Listing of equity shares in the U.K. are required under the Listing Rules to report on how they have applied the Combined Code in their annual report and accounts.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] It further demonstrates the relationship that subsists among shareholders, management, and the independent audit teams.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] Financial statements must be prepared using a particular set of rules and regulations hence the rationale behind allowing the companies to apply the provisions of company law, international financial reporting standards (IFRS), as well as the U.K. stock exchange rules as directed by the FCA.
[src:aws-organizations/regulatory-compliance] It is also possible that shareholders may not understand the figures as presented in the various financial statements, hence it is critical that the board should provide notes on accounting policies as well as other explanatory notes to help them understand the report better.
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] In computer programming, **resource management** refers to techniques for managing resources (components with limited availability).
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] Computer programs may manage their own resources by using features exposed by programming languages (Elder, Jackson & Liblit (2008) is a survey article contrasting different approaches), or may elect to manage them by a host – an operating system or virtual machine – or another program.
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] Host-based management is known as *resource tracking,* and consists of cleaning up resource leaks: terminating access to resources that have been acquired but not released after use.
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] This is known as *reclaiming* resources, and is analogous to garbage collection for memory.
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] On many systems, the operating system reclaims resources after the process makes the exit system call.
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] The omission of releasing a resource when a program has finished using it is known as a resource leak, and is an issue in sequential computing.
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] Multiple processes wish to access a limited resource can be an issue in concurrent computing, and is known as resource contention.
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] Resource management seeks to control access in order to prevent both of these situations.
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] Formally, resource management (preventing resource leaks) consists of ensuring that a resource is released if and only if it is successfully acquired.
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] This general problem can be abstracted as "*before,* *body,* and *after*" code, which normally are executed in this order, with the condition that the *after* code is called if and only if the *before* code successfully completes, regardless of whether the *body* code executes successfully or not.
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] This is also known as *execute around* or a *code sandwich,* and occurs in various other contexts, such as a temporary change of program state, or tracing entry and exit into a subroutine.
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] However, resource management is the most commonly cited application.
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] In aspect-oriented programming, such execute around logic is a form of *advice*.
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] In the terminology of control flow analysis, resource release must postdominate successful resource acquisition; failure to ensure this is a bug, and a code path that violates this condition causes a resource leak.
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] Resource leaks are often minor problems, generally not crashing the program, but instead causing some slowdown to the program or the overall system.
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] However, they may cause crashes – either the program itself or other programs – due to *resource exhaustion:* if the system runs out of resources, acquisition requests fail.
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] This can present a security bug if an attack can cause resource exhaustion.
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] Resource leaks may happen under regular program flow – such as simply forgetting to release a resource – or only in exceptional circumstances, such as when a resource is not released if there is an exception in another part of the program.
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] Resource leaks are very frequently caused by early exit from a subroutine, either by a `return` statement, or an exception raised either by the subroutine itself, or a deeper subroutine that it calls.
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] While resource release due to return statements can be handled by carefully releasing within the subroutine before the return, exceptions cannot be handled without some additional language facility that guarantees that release code is executed.
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] More subtly, successful resource acquisition must dominate resource release, as otherwise the code will try to release a resource it has not acquired.
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] The consequences of such an incorrect release range from being silently ignored to crashing the program or unpredictable behavior.
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] These bugs generally manifest rarely, as they require resource allocation to first fail, which is generally an exceptional case.
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] Further, the consequences may not be serious, as the program may already be crashing due to failure to acquire an essential resource.
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] However, these can prevent recovery from the failure, or turn an orderly shutdown into a disorderly shutdown.
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] In computer science, resource contention refers to a conflict that arises when multiple entities attempt to access a shared resource, like random access memory, disk storage, cache memory, internal buses, or external network devices.
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] Memory can be treated as a resource, but memory management is usually considered separately, primarily because memory allocation and deallocation is significantly more frequent than acquisition and release of other resources, such as file handles.
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] Memory managed by an *external* system has similarities to both (internal) memory management (since it is memory) and resource management (since it is managed by an external system).
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] Examples include memory managed via native code and used from Java (via Java Native Interface); and objects in the Document Object Model (DOM), used from JavaScript.
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] In both these cases, the memory manager (garbage collector) of the runtime environment (virtual machine) is unable to manage the external memory (there is no shared memory management), and thus the external memory is treated as a resource, and managed analogously.
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] However, cycles between systems (JavaScript referring to the DOM, referring back to JavaScript) can make management difficult or impossible.
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] Lexical management, when applicable, allows a better separation of concerns and is less error-prone.
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] This is correct if the intervening `...` code does not contain an early exit (`return`), the language does not have exceptions, and `open` is guaranteed to succeed.
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] However, it causes a resource leak if there is a return or exception, and causes an incorrect release of unacquired resource if `open` can fail.
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] There are two more fundamental problems: the acquisition-release pair is not adjacent (the release code must be written far from the acquisition code), and resource management is not encapsulated – the programmer must manually ensure that they are always paired.
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] In combination, these mean that acquisition and release must be explicitly paired, but cannot be placed together, thus making it easy for these to not be paired correctly.
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] This ensures correct release even if there is a return within the body or an exception thrown.
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] Further, note that the acquisition occurs *before* the `try` clause, ensuring that the `finally` clause is only executed if the `open` code succeeds (without throwing an exception), assuming that "no exception" means "success" (as is the case for `open` in Python).
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] While this ensures correct resource management, it fails to provide adjacency or encapsulation.
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] There are many variations in the implementation, and there are also significantly different approaches.
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] The most common approach to resource management across languages is to use unwind protection, which is called when execution exits a scope – by execution running off the end of the block, returning from within the block, or an exception being thrown.
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] This works for stack-managed resources, and is implemented in many languages, including C#, Common Lisp, Java, Python, Ruby, and Scheme.
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] The main problems with this approach is that the release code (most commonly in a `finally` clause) may be very distant from the acquisition code (it lacks *adjacency*), and that the acquisition and release code must always be paired by the caller (it lacks *encapsulation*).
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] An alternative, more imperative approach, is to write asynchronous code in direct style: acquire a resource, and then in the next line have a *deferred* release, which is called when the scope is exited – synchronous acquisition followed by asynchronous release.
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] This originated in C++ as the ScopeGuard class, by Andrei Alexandrescu and Petru Marginean in 2000, with improvements by Joshua Lehrer, and has direct language support in D via the `scope` keyword (ScopeGuardStatement), where it is one approach to exception safety, in addition to RAII (see below).
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] It has also been included in Go, as the `defer` statement.
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] This approach lacks encapsulation – one must explicitly match acquisition and release – but avoids having to create an object for each resource (code-wise, avoid writing a class for each type of resource).
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] In object-oriented programming, resources are encapsulated within objects that use them, such as a `file` object having a field whose value is a file descriptor (or more general file handle).
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] This allows the object to use and manage the resource without users of the object needing to do so.
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] However, there is a wide variety of ways that objects and resources can be related.
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] Firstly, there is the question of ownership: does an object *have* a resource?
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] Most common is to acquire a resource during object creation, and then explicitly release it via an instance method, commonly called `dispose`.
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] This is analogous to traditional file management (acquire during `open`, release by explicit `close`), and is known as the dispose pattern.
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] This is the basic approach used in several major modern object-oriented languages, including Java, C# and Python, and these languages have additional constructs to automate resource management.
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] However, even in these languages, more complex object relationships result in more complex resource management, as discussed below.
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] A natural approach is to make holding a resource be a class invariant: resources are acquired during object creation (specifically initialization), and released during object destruction (specifically finalization).
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] This is known as Resource Acquisition Is Initialization (RAII), and ties resource management to object lifetime, ensuring that live objects have all necessary resources.
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] Other approaches do not make holding the resource a class invariant, and thus objects may not have necessary resources (because they've not been acquired yet, have already been released, or are being managed externally), resulting in errors such as trying to read from a closed file.
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] This approach ties resource management to memory management (specifically object management), so if there are no memory leaks (no object leaks), there are no resource leaks.
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] RAII works naturally for heap-managed resources, not only stack-managed resources, and is composable: resources held by objects in arbitrarily complicated relationships (a complicated object graph) are released transparently simply by object destruction (so long as this is done properly!).
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] Firstly, because resources are expensive, it is desirable to release them promptly, so objects holding resources should be destroyed as soon as they become garbage (are no longer in use).
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] However, most modern automatic memory management is non-deterministic, making no guarantees that objects will be destroyed promptly or even at all!
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] This is because it is cheaper to leave some garbage allocated than to precisely collect each object immediately on its becoming garbage.
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] Secondly, releasing resources during object destruction means that an object must have a *finalizer* (in deterministic memory management known as a *destructor*) – the object cannot simply be deallocated – which significantly complicates and slows garbage collection.
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] When multiple objects rely on a single resource, resource management can be complicated.
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] A fundamental question is whether a "has a" relationship is one of *owning* another object (object composition), or *viewing* another object (object aggregation).
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] A common case is when one two objects are chained, as in pipe and filter pattern, the delegation pattern, the decorator pattern, or the adapter pattern.
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] If the second object (which is not used directly) holds a resource, is the first object (which is used directly) responsible for managing the resource?
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] This is generally answered identically to whether the first object *owns* the second object: if so, then the owning object is also responsible for resource management ("having a resource" is transitive), while if not, then it is not.
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] Further, a single object may "have" several other objects, owning some and viewing others.
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] Both cases are commonly found, and conventions differ.
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] In object aggregation, nothing needs to be done by the viewing object, as it is not responsible for the resource.
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] For example, in the Java Class Library, `Reader#close()` closes the underlying stream, and these can be chained.
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] For example, a `BufferedReader` may contain a `InputStreamReader`, which in turn contains a `FileInputStream`, and calling `close` on the `BufferedReader` in turn closes the `InputStreamReader`, which in turn closes the `FileInputStream`, which in turn releases the system file resource.
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] By contrast, in Python, a csv.reader does not own the `file` that it is reading, so there is no need (and it is not possible) to close the reader, and instead the `file` itself must be closed.
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] Various mechanisms exist to allow greater control of resource management.
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] For example, in the Google Closure Library, the `goog.Disposable` class provides a `registerDisposable` method to register other objects to be disposed with this object, together with various lower-level instance and class methods to manage disposal.
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] In structured programming, stack resource management is done simply by nesting code sufficiently to handle all cases.
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] This requires only a single return at the end of the code, and can result in heavily nested code if many resources must be acquired, which is considered an anti-pattern by some – the *Arrow Anti Pattern,* due to the triangular shape from the successive nesting.
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] One other approach, which allows early return but consolidates cleanup in one place, is to have a single exit return of a function, preceded by cleanup code, and to use goto to jump to the cleanup before exit.
[src:aws-organizations/resource-management-computing] This is infrequently seen in modern code, but occurs in some uses of C.
